{"title_page": "George Mason University", "text_new": "{{short description|Public liberal arts and research university in Fairfax, Virginia}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = George Mason University <br> \uc870\uc9c0\uba54\uc774\uc2a8\ub300\ud559\uad50\n| image_name = George Mason University logo.svg\n| image_size = 200\n| motto = Freedom and Learning\n| established = October 1, 1949<ref name=\"Finley\" />{{rp|5}} <br> ([[University of Virginia]])\n| type = [[Public University]] <br> [[Research University]]\n| academic_affiliations = [[Association of Public and Land-grant Universities|APLU]]<br />[[Oak Ridge Associated Universities|ORAU]]<br />[[Southeastern Universities Research Association|SURA]] <br> [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools|SACS]] <br> [[Ministry of Education (South Korea)|MOE-ROK]]\n| staff = 2,497 total (763 administrative faculty; 1,734 classified staff)<ref>https://irr2.gmu.edu/New/N_Faculty/WEB%20Faculty_Staff%20by%20Gender%20and%20Race_Ethnicity.htm (Fall 2016)</ref>\n| endowment = [[United States dollar|US$]]113 million (December 2019)<ref>George Mason Board of Visitors Meeting Book; http://bov.gmu.edu/wp-content/uploads/FINAL-full-board-meeting-december-12-2019-1.pdf</ref>\n| president = [[Gregory Washington]]<ref>{{cite web |title=George Mason selects dean of UC-Irvine engineering school as its next president |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2020/02/24/george-mason-selects-dean-uc-irvine-engineering-school-its-next-president/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n| provost = S. David Wu (outgoing)\n| academic_staff = 2,609 total (1,260 full-time; 1,349 part-time)<ref name=\"frb1\">{{cite web |url=https://irr2.gmu.edu/cds/cds_new/sec_action.cfm?year=2016-17&sec_id=A |title=Current Facts and Figures |publisher=George Mason University}}</ref>\n| students = 38,255<ref name=\"frb1\"/>\n| undergrad = 26,013 (2019-2020)<ref name=\"frb1\"/>\n| postgrad = 11,201 (2019\u20132020)<ref name=\"frb1\"/>\n| city = [[Arlington County, Virginia|Arlington]] (urban), [[Virginia|VA]], [[United States|US]]; [[Fairfax, Virginia|Fairfax City]]-[[Fairfax County, Virginia|Fairfax County]] (suburban), [[Virginia|VA]], [[United States|US]]; [[Front Royal]] (rural-exurban), [[Virginia|VA]], [[United States|US]]; [[Prince William County, Virginia|Prince William]] (suburban), [[Virginia|VA]], [[United States|US]]; [[Songdo International Business District|Songdo]] (urban IBD), [[Incheon Free Economic Zone|Incheon]] ([[Free Economic Zone|FEZ]]), [[South Korea]].<ref name=\"ifez1\">{{Cite news |last=Sang |first=Youn-joo |title=IFEZ Rises as Global Investment Center |work=Korea Herald |location=Seoul, Korea |accessdate=September 26, 2015 |date=May 14, 2015 |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20150514000742}}</ref><ref name=ifex2>{{Cite news |last=Kim |first=Rahn |title=8 in 10 International School Students in Korea Are Koreans |work=Korea Times |accessdate= September 26, 2015 |date=February 11, 2015 |url=http://www.koreatimesus.com/8-in-10-international-school-students-in-korea-are-koreans/}}</ref>\n| coor = {{Coord|38.831|-77.308|type:edu_region:US-VA|display=title}}\n| campus = Mostly [[Suburb]]an, {{convert|1148|acre|km2}} total across 4 Virginia campuses<br />{{convert|953|acre|km2}} Fairfax Campus (headquarters)\n| colors = Green and Gold<ref>{{cite web |url=http://brand.gmu.edu/visual-identity-and-style/color/ |title=Color |publisher=gmu.edu|website = The George Mason University Brand Profile |accessdate=}}</ref><br />{{color box|#006633}}&nbsp;{{color box|#FFCC33}}\n| sporting_affiliations = [[NCAA Division I]] \u2013 [[Atlantic 10 Conference|A-10]]\n| nickname = [[George Mason Patriots|Patriots]]\n| mascot = The Patriot<br />\n| website = {{Official URL}}\n| logo = George Mason University seal.svg\n| logo_size = 200\n}}\n\n'''George Mason University''' ('''Mason''', '''GMU,''' '''George Mason,''' or {{Lang-ko|'''\uc870\uc9c0\uba54\uc774\uc2a8\ub300\ud559\uad50'''|translit=jojimeiseundaehaggyo}}) is a public [[research university]] located in [[Fairfax County, Virginia|Fairfax County]] near [[Fairfax, Virginia|Fairfax City]] in [[Virginia]].<ref>Mason Spirit, Published by the Office of University Development and Alumni Affairs in conjunction with the Office of University Relations. Kearney Rich, Colleen. \"From the Archives: What's in a Name?\" Original: Mason Spirit. Winter. 2006. Web: http://spirit.gmu.edu/2012/04/from-the-archives-whats-in-a-name/</ref> In 1956, the Commonwealth of Virginia authorized the establishment of a [[Northern Virginia]] branch of the [[University of Virginia]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ahistoryofmason.gmu.edu/items/show/18 |title=A History of George Mason University {{!}} Commonwealth of Virginia: House Joint Resolution #5, February 24, 1956.|website=ahistoryofmason.gmu.edu|access-date=June 12, 2019}}</ref> and the institution that is now named George Mason University opened in September 1957.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ahistoryofmason.gmu.edu/about|title=A History of George Mason University {{!}} About George Mason University: A History|website=ahistoryofmason.gmu.edu|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> It became an independent institution in 1972.<ref name=\"Finley\" />  It has since grown to become the largest four-year public university in the Commonwealth of Virginia. The university is named after the founding father [[George Mason]], a Virginia [[Planter (American South)|planter]] and politician who authored the [[Virginia Declaration of Rights]] that later influenced the future [[United States Bill of Rights|Bill of Rights]] of the [[Constitution of the United States|United States Constitution]]. Mason operates four campuses in Virginia ([[Fairfax County, Virginia|Fairfax]], [[Arlington County, Virginia|Arlington]], [[Front Royal, Virginia|Front Royal]], and [[Prince William County, Virginia|Prince William]]), as well as a fifth campus in [[Songdo International Business District|Songdo]] ([[Incheon Free Economic Zone|Incheon]]), [[South Korea]]\n\nThe university is [[Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education|classified]] among \"R1: Doctoral Universities \u2013 Very high research activity\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://carnegieclassifications.iu.edu/lookup/view_institution.php?unit_id=232186 |title=Carnegie Classification |publisher=[[Indiana University]] |date=2019 |accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref> It is particularly well known in the fields of [[economics]] and [[law and economics]]. Two Mason economics professors have won the [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economics]]: [[James M. Buchanan]] in 1986 and [[Vernon L. Smith]] in 2002.<ref>[http://walterewilliams.com/another-nobel-laureate/ Another Nobel Laureate] Walter E. Williams, GMU, Department of Economics, October 14, 2002</ref>\n\n[[EagleBank Arena]] (formerly the Patriot Center), a 10,000-seat arena and concert venue operated by the university, is located on the main Fairfax campus. The university recognizes 500 student groups as well as 41 fraternities and sororities.\n\n==History==\n===Timeline from center to college then university===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Institution Name\n! Institution Location\n! Institution Executive\n|-\n|1949\n| Northern Virginia University Center of the University of Virginia<ref name=\"Mann papers\">{{cite book |last1=Mann |first1=C. Harrison |title=C. Harrison Mann, Jr. papers |date=1832\u20131979 |publisher=George Mason University. Libraries. Special Collections Research Center |location=Arlington, Virginia |url=http://sca.gmu.edu/finding_aids/mann.html |accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n| Arlington\n| Director John Norville Gibson Finley<ref name=\"Finley\">{{Cite book |last=Finley |first=John Norville Gibson |title=Progress Report of the Northern Virginia University Center |date=July 1, 1952 |url=http://digilib.gmu.edu/jspui/bitstream/handle/1920/2698/Mann_53_1_1_v.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y|archive-date=2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220225740/http://digilib.gmu.edu/jspui/bitstream/handle/1920/2698/Mann_53_1_1_v.pdf |quote=\"The report that follows is a progress report on the Northern Virginia University Center since its beginnings in 1949 by its Local Director, Professor J. N. G. Finley.\" George B. Zehmer, Director Extension Division University of Virginia}}</ref>\n|-\n|1956\n| University College of the University of Virginia<ref name=\"House Joint Resolution 5\">{{cite book |last1=Mann, Jr. |first1=C. Harrison |title=House Joint Resolution 5 |date=Feb 24, 1956 |publisher=Virginia General Assembly |location=Richmond |page=1 |url=http://ahistoryofmason.gmu.edu/archive/files/8e80e948d96eba1ccf790954fb595bc5.jpg}}</ref>\n| Bailey's Crossroads\n| Director John Norville Gibson Finley<ref name=\"Finley\"/>\n|-\n| 1959\n| George Mason College of the University of Virginia<ref name=\"McFarlane papers\">{{cite book |last1=McFarlane |first1=William Hugh |title=William Hugh McFarlane George Mason University history collection |date=1949\u20131977 |publisher=George Mason University Special Collections and Archives |location=Fairfax, VA |url=http://ead.lib.virginia.edu/vivaxtf/view?do |accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Board of Visitors |title=Meeting Minutes |date=December 12, 1959 |publisher=University of Virginia}}</ref>\n| Bailey's Crossroads\n| Director John Norville Gibson Finley<ref name=\"Finley\"/>\n|-\n| 1964\n| George Mason College of the University of Virginia<ref>{{cite news |title=Press release |url=http://ahistoryofmason.gmu.edu/items/show/309 |accessdate=February 23, 2017 |publisher=George Mason College of the University of Virginia |date=September 14, 1964}}</ref>\n| Bailey's Crossroads (Jan. 1964 to June 1964), later Fairfax (beginning Sept. 1964)\n| Director Robert Reid<ref>{{cite news |publisher=The Virginian |date=July 31, 1964 |title=George Mason University Public Relations Newsclippings 1964 Box 1 Folder 16}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1966\n| George Mason College of the University of Virginia\n| Fairfax\n| Chancellor Lorin A. Thompson<ref>{{cite book |last1=Virginia Advisory Legislative Council |title=The Crisis in Higher Education in Virginia and a Solution |date=August 15, 1955 |publisher=Virginia General Assembly |location=Richmond |page=13 |url=http://ahistoryofmason.gmu.edu/items/show/17 |accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1972\n| George Mason College of the University of Virginia\n| Fairfax\n| President Lorin A. Thompson<ref name=\"Netherton\">{{Cite book |publisher=Fairfax County Board of Supervisors |isbn=978-0-9601630-1-4 |last=Netherton |first=Nan |title=Fairfax County, Virginia: A History |date=January 1, 1978}}{{rp|588}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1973\n| George Mason College of the University of Virginia\n| Fairfax\n| President Vergil H. Dykstra<ref name=\"Netherton\"/>\n|-\n| 1977\n| George Mason University\n| Fairfax\n| President Robert C. Krug<ref>{{Cite book |publisher=Marquis Academic Media |title=Yearbook of Higher Education |date=October 1, 1978}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1979\n| George Mason University\n| Fairfax\n| President George W. Johnson<ref name=\"Pacheco\">{{Cite book |publisher=Associated University Presses |isbn=978-0-913969-00-7 |last=Pacheco |first=Josephine F. |title=The Legacy of George Mason |date=January 1, 1983}}{{rp|23}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1979\n| George Mason University\n| Fairfax, Arlington\n| President George W. Johnson<ref name=\"Pacheco\"/>\n|-\n| 1996\n| George Mason University\n| Fairfax, Arlington\n| President [[Alan G. Merten]]<ref name=\"Vise\">{{Cite news |title=Alan G. Merten to retire as George Mason University president |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/alan-g-merten-to-retire-as-george-mason-university-president/2011/03/23/ABConfJB_story.html |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=March 23, 2011|access-date = April 23, 2015 |issn=0190-8286 |first=Daniel de |last=Vise |first2=and Lisa |last2=Rein}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1997\n| George Mason University\n| Fairfax, Arlington, Prince William\n| President [[Alan G. Merten]]<ref name=\"Vise\"/>\n|-\n| 2005\n| George Mason University\n| Fairfax, Arlington, Prince William, Ras al Khayma<ref name=\"Ras al Khaym\">{{Cite news |title=George Mason University, Among First With an Emirates Branch, Is Pulling Out |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/01/education/01campus.html |newspaper=New York Times |date=February 28, 2009 |access-date = Dec 22, 2015 |issn= |first=Tamar |last=Lewin}}</ref>\n| President [[Alan G. Merten]]<ref name=\"Vise\"/>\n|-\n| 2009\n| George Mason University\n| Fairfax, Arlington, Prince William\n| President [[Alan G. Merten]]<ref name=\"Ras al Khaym\" />\n|-\n| 2011\n| George Mason University\n| Fairfax, Arlington, Prince William, Front Royal\n| President [[Alan G. Merten]]<ref name=\"Vise\"/>\n|-\n| 2012\n| George Mason University\n| Fairfax, Arlington, Prince William, Front Royal\n| President [[\u00c1ngel Cabrera (academic)|\u00c1ngel Cabrera]]<ref name=\"Pearlstein\">{{Cite news |last=Pearlstein |first=Steven |title=Four tough things universities should do to rein in costs |work=The Washington Post |location=Washington, DC |date=November 25, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2012\n| George Mason University\n| Fairfax, Arlington, Prince William, Front Royal, Songdo\n| President [[\u00c1ngel Cabrera (academic)|\u00c1ngel Cabrera]]<ref name=\"Pearlstein\"/>\n|}\n\n===University of Virginia (1949\u20131972)===\n[[File:George Mason College, Fairfax campus, 1967, aerial photograph looking north.jpg|thumb|Aerial photograph taken in 1967 showing what was then called George Mason College]]\n[[File:George Mason College, decal, ca. 1970.jpg|right|thumb|Decal from when George Mason College was a part of the University of Virginia]]\nThe [[University of Virginia]] in [[Charlottesville]] created an extension center to serve [[Northern Virginia]].<ref>{{Citation |last=Steele |first=Clarence A. |title=Clarence A. Steele to Colgate W. Darden, Jr., April 4, 1949 |date=April 4, 1949}}</ref> \"\u2026 the University Center opened, on October 1, 1949...\"<ref name=\"Finley\"/> The extension center offered both for credit and non-credit informal classes in the evenings in the Vocational Building of the [[Washington-Lee High School]] in [[Arlington, Virginia]], at schools in [[Alexandria, Virginia|Alexandria]], [[Fairfax, Virginia|Fairfax]], and [[Prince William, Virginia|Prince William]], at federal buildings, at churches, at the [[Virginia Theological Seminary]], and at [[Marine Corps Base Quantico]], and even in a few private homes.<ref name=\"Finley\"/>{{rp|5}} The first for credit classes offered were: \"Government in the Far East, Introduction to International Politics, English Composition, Principles of Economics, Mathematical Analysis, Introduction to Mathematical Statistics, and Principles of Lip Reading.\"<ref name=\"Finley\"/>  By the end of 1952, enrollment increased to 1,192 students from 665 students the previous year.<ref name=\"Finley\"/>\n\nA resolution of the [[Virginia General Assembly]] in January 1956 changed the extension center into University College, the [[Northern Virginia]] branch of the [[University of Virginia]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1919\">{{Cite book |publisher=Lulu.com |isbn=978-1-329-31719-2 |last=Anderson |first=Keith |title=The Los Angeles State Normal School, UCLA's Forgotten Past: 1881\u20131919 |date=August 29, 2015}}{{rp|158}}{{self-published source|date=February 2020}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}} John Norville Gibson Finley served as director.<ref>{{Citation |last=Teachman |first=A. Ellis |title=Photograph: J.N.G. Finley |date=September 6, 2007 |url=http://mars.gmu.edu/handle/1920/2712}}</ref> Seventeen freshmen students attended classes at University College in a small renovated elementary school building in [[Bailey's Crossroads]] starting in September 1957.<ref name=\"Cristian2009\">{{Cite journal |publisher=Catholic University of America |last=Cristian |first=Viviana |title=Who are We?: Cultural Identity Among Latino College Students in Northern Virginia |location=Washington, DC |date=2009}}{{rp|24}}</ref> In 1958 University College became George Mason College.<ref name=\"autogenerated1919\"/>\n\nThe [[City of Fairfax, VA|City of Fairfax]] purchased and donated {{convert|150|acre|km2}} of land just south of the city limits to the University of Virginia for the college's new site, which is now referred to as the [[George Mason University Fairfax Campus|Fairfax Campus]]. In 1959, the [[Board of Visitors]] of the University of Virginia selected a permanent name for the college: George Mason College of the University of Virginia. The Fairfax campus construction planning that began in early 1960 showed visible results when the development of the first {{convert|40|acre|m2}} of Fairfax Campus began in 1962. In the Fall of 1964 the new campus welcomed 356 students.<ref>{{Cite book |publisher=Lulu.com |isbn=978-1-329-31719-2 |last=Anderson |first=Keith |title=The Los Angeles State Normal School, UCLA's Forgotten Past: 1881\u20131919 |date=August 29, 2015}}{{rp|185}}{{self-published source|date=February 2020}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}}\n\nDuring the 1966 Session of the [[Virginia General Assembly]], Alexandria delegate [[James M. Thomson (Virginia)|James M. Thomson]], with the backing of the University of Virginia, introduced a bill in the General Assembly to make George Mason College a four-year institution under the University of Virginia's direction. The measure, known as H 33,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ahistoryofmason.gmu.edu/items/show/98 |title=A History of George Mason University \u2013 Acts of Assembly, Chapter 68 [H33] Article 8. George Mason College, March 1, 1966. |work=gmu.edu}}</ref> passed the Assembly easily and was approved on March 1, 1966 making George Mason College a degree-granting institution. During that same year, the local jurisdictions of [[Fairfax County, Virginia|Fairfax County]], [[Arlington County, Virginia|Arlington County]], and the cities of [[Alexandria, Virginia|Alexandria]] and [[Falls Church, Virginia|Falls Church]] agreed to appropriate $3 million to purchase land adjacent to Mason to provide for a {{convert|600|acre|km2|adj=on}} Fairfax Campus with the intention that the institution would expand into a regional university of major proportions, including the granting of graduate degrees.\n\n===George Mason University (1972\u2013present)===\n{{update|section|date=May 2017}}\nOn Friday, April 7, 1972, a contingent from George Mason College, led by Chancellor Lorin A. Thompson, met with Virginia Governor [[A. Linwood Holton]] at Richmond. They were there to participate in the governor's signing into law Virginia General Assembly Bill H 210 separating George Mason College from the University of Virginia at Charlottesville and renaming it George Mason University.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ahistoryofmason.gmu.edu/exhibits/show/independence/contents/independence |title=A History of George Mason University \u2013 1972\u20131978: Independence : Independence, April 7, 1972 |work=gmu.edu}}</ref>\nIn 1978, [[George W. Johnson (academic)|George W. Johnson]] was appointed to serve as the fourth president.<ref name=\"Johnson Obit\" /> Under his eighteen-year tenure, the university expanded both its physical size and program offerings at a tremendous rate.<ref name=\"Johnson Obit\">{{cite news |first=T. Rees |last=Shapiro |title=George W. Johnson, college president who transformed GMU, dies at 88 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/george-w-johnson-college-president-who-transformed-gmu-dies-at-88/2017/06/03/473a9fe2-4875-11e7-bcde-624ad94170ab_story.html |work=[[Washington Post]] |publisher= |date=June 3, 2017 |accessdate=June 24, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"gmupres\">{{cite news |first= |last= |title=Office of the President: Mason's Presidents |url=https://president.gmu.edu/masons-presidents/ |work=George Mason University |publisher= |date= |accessdate=June 24, 2017}}</ref> Shortly before Johnson's inauguration in April 1979, Mason acquired the [[George Mason University School of Law|School of Law]] and the new Arlington Campus. The university also became a doctoral institution.<ref name=\"Johnson Obit\" /> Toward the end of Johnson's term, Mason would be deep in planning for a third campus in [[Prince William County, Virginia|Prince William County]] at [[Manassas, VA|Manassas]]. Major campus facilities, such as Student Union Building II, [[EagleBank Arena]], Center for the Arts, and the Johnson Learning Center, were all constructed over the course of Johnson's eighteen years as University President. Enrollment once again more than doubled from 10,767 during the fall of 1978 to 24,368 in the spring of 1996.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ahistoryofmason.gmu.edu/exhibits/show/prominence/contents/introduction |title=A History of George Mason University \u2013 1978\u20131996: Emergence : Introduction |work=gmu.edu}}</ref>\n[[File:Governor A. Linwood Holton signs H-210 separating George Mason College from the University of Virginia, April 7, 1972.jpg|left|thumb|Governor A. Linwood Holton signs H\u2011210 separating George Mason College from the University of Virginia, April 7, 1972]]\nDr. [[Alan Merten|Alan G. Merten]] was appointed president in 1996. He believed that the university's location made it responsible for both contributing to and drawing from its surrounding communities\u2014local, national, and global. George Mason was becoming recognized and acclaimed in all of these spheres. During Merten's tenure, the university hosted the World Congress of Information Technology in 1998,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wcit2014.org/history/ |title=History |work=WCIT |accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref> celebrated a second [[Nobel Memorial Prize]]-winning faculty member in 2002, and cheered the [[George Mason Patriots#Men's Basketball|Men's Basketball]] team in their [[NCAA]] [[Final Four (college basketball)|Final Four]] appearance in 2006. Enrollment increased from just over 24,000 students in 1996 to approximately 33,000 during the spring semester of 2012, making Mason Virginia's largest public university and gained prominence at the national level.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ahistoryofmason.gmu.edu/exhibits/show/presence/contents/introduction |title=A History of George Mason University \u2013 1996\u20132012: Prominence : Introduction |work=gmu.edu}}</ref>\n\nDr. [[\u00c1ngel Cabrera (academic)|\u00c1ngel Cabrera]] officially took office on July 1, 2012. Both Cabrera and the board were well aware that Mason was part of a rapidly changing academia, full of challenges to the viability of higher education. In a resolution on August 17, 2012, the board asked Dr. Cabrera to create a new strategic vision that would help Mason remain relevant and competitive in the future. The drafting of the Vision for Mason, from conception to official outline, created a new mission statement that defines the university.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://vision.gmu.edu/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/MasonVision.pdf |title=Mason Vision |website=vision.gmu.edu}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, 2013, university president \u00c1ngel Cabrera held a press conference to formally announce the university's decision to leave the [[Colonial Athletic Association]] to join the [[Atlantic 10 Conference]] (A-10). The announcement came just days after the Board of Visitors' approval of the university's Vision document that Dr. Cabrera had overseen. Mason began competition in the A-10 during the 2013\u20132014 academic year, and Mason's association with the institutions that comprise the A-10 started a new chapter in Mason athletics, academics, and other aspects of university life.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ahistoryofmason.gmu.edu/exhibits/show/vision/contents/a10 |title=A History of George Mason University \u2013 2012\u2013present: Vision : Mason Moves from the Colonial Athletic Association to the Atlantic 10 Conference |work=gmu.edu}}</ref>  ''[[The Chronicle of Higher Education]]'' listed Mason as one of the \"Great Colleges to Work For\" from 2010\u20132014.<ref name=\"GreatColleges\">{{cite web |last1=ModernThink LLC |title=Great Colleges to Work For |publisher=The Chronicle of Higher Education |url=http://chroniclegreatcolleges.com/dev/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/2014-Colleges-Recognized-by-Enrollment-Size-and-Category.pdf |website=chroniclegreatcolleges.com |accessdate=April 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709034100/http://chroniclegreatcolleges.com/dev/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/2014-Colleges-Recognized-by-Enrollment-Size-and-Category.pdf|archive-date=July 9, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' listed Mason as one of the \"Top Workplaces\" in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=Top Workplaces 2014 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-tran/capital-business/top-workplaces |website=Washington Post |accessdate=April 24, 2015}}</ref> The [[WorldatWork]] Alliance for Work-Life Progress awarded Mason the Seal of Distinction in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=WorldatWork |url=http://www.worldatwork.org/waw/adimLink?id=78343 |website=www.worldatwork.org |accessdate=April 24, 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150318180954/http://www.worldatwork.org/waw/adimLink?id=78343|archive-date = March 18, 2015|url-status = dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[AARP]] listed Mason as one of the Best Employers for Workers Over 50 in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=Employers \u2013 George Mason University, Life Planning Seminars for 50-plus Workers |url=http://www.aarp.org/work/2013-aarp-best-employers/george-mason-university-aarp-best-employers/ |accessdate=April 24, 2015 |publisher=AARP}}</ref> [[Phi Beta Kappa]] established a chapter at the university in 2013.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nIn 2018, a [[Freedom of Information Act]] lawsuit revealed that conservative donors, including the [[Charles Koch Foundation]] and [[Federalist Society]], were given direct influence over faculty hiring decisions at the university's law and economics schools. GMU President \u00c1ngel Cabrera acknowledged that the revelations raised questions about the university's academic integrity and pledged to prohibit donors from sitting on faculty selection committees in the future.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/05/us/koch-donors-george-mason.html |title=What Charles Koch and Other Donors to George Mason University Got for Their Money |first1=Erica L. |last1=Green |first2=Stephanie |last2=Saul |date=May 5, 2018 |publisher= |via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nDr. [[\u00c1ngel Cabrera (academic)|\u00c1ngel Cabrera]] resigned his position and became president of [[Georgia Tech]]. The interim president was [[Anne Holton|Anne B. Holton]].\n\nOn February 24, 2020, the Board of Visitors appointed Dr. [[Gregory Washington]] as the eighth president. He will officially start at George Mason on July 1, 2020. Dr. Washington is the university's first African-American president.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.gmu.edu/news/583236|title=Gregory Washington named George Mason University\u2019s 8th president &#124; George Mason|website=www2.gmu.edu}}</ref>\n\n==Campuses==\n{{Location map+ | Earth\n| caption =\n| width = 450\n| float = left\n| places =\n  {{Location map~ | Earth\n    | label =Virginia Campuses\n    | position =bottom\n    | lat_deg =38.8316341\n    | lon_deg =-77.3110481\n    }}\n  {{Location map~ | Earth\n    | label =Songdo Campus\n    | position =bottom\n    | lat_deg =37.3752488\n    | lon_deg =126.6665496\n    }}\n}}\n\n{{Location map+ | USA Virginia Northern\n| caption =\n| places =\n  {{Location map~ | USA Virginia Northern\n    | label =Fairfax\n    | position =right\n    | lat_deg =38.8316341\n    | lon_deg =-77.3110481\n    }}\n  {{Location map~ | USA Virginia Northern\n    | label =Arlington\n    | position =left\n    | lat_deg =38.8852052\n    | lon_deg =-77.1024739\n    }}\n  {{Location map~ | USA Virginia Northern\n    | label =Science{{nbsp}}and Technology\n    | position =bottom\n    | lat_deg =38.7562587\n    | lon_deg =-77.5235441\n    }}\n  {{Location map~ | USA Virginia Northern\n    | label =Smithsonian{{nbh}}Mason School{{nbsp}}of{{nbsp}}Conservation\n    | position =right\n    | lat_deg =38.8872578\n    | lon_deg =-78.1657575\n    }}\n}}\nGeorge Mason University has four campuses in the United States, all within the Commonwealth of Virginia.<ref name=distributedcampusmodel /> Three are within the [[Northern Virginia]] section of the [[Piedmont region of Virginia|Piedmont]], and one in the [[Blue Ridge Mountains]] region.<ref name=distributedcampusmodel /> The university has one campus in [[South Korea]], within the [[Incheon Free Economic Zone]] of the [[Songdo International Business District|Songdo]] region.<ref>{{cite act |number=23.1\u20131504 |year=2016 |url=http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/title23.1/chapter15/section23.1-1504/}}</ref><ref name=\"distributedcampusmodel\">{{cite web |url=http://provostblog.gmu.edu/archives/215 |title=Distributed Campuses |author=Office of the Provost, George Mason University |work=gmu.edu|access-date=February 5, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304233129/http://provostblog.gmu.edu/archives/215|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The university had a campus at [[Ras al-Khaimah]], but that location is now closed.<ref name=\"Ras al Khaym\" /> The Blue Ridge campus, just outside Front Royal, is run in cooperation with the [[Smithsonian Institution]].<ref name=factsheet />{{Clear}}\n\n=== Fairfax ===\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Fairfax Campus\n| subdivision_name4               = \n[[Fairfax, Virginia|Fairfax]]\n| subdivision_type6               = \n| parts                           = Shenandoah <br> Rappahannock <br> Aquia <ref>https://housing.gmu.edu/about</ref>\n| parts_type                      = List of Housing Neighborhoods\n| image_map                       = {{Location map+ | GMU Fairfax\n| width =300\n| places =\n  {{Location map~ | GMU Fairfax\n    | label =Fenwick Library\n    | label_size=50\n    | position =top\n    | lat_deg =38.8323371\n    | lon_deg =-77.3084143\n    }}\n  {{Location map~ | GMU Fairfax\n    | label =Johnson Center\n    | label_size=50\n    | position =right\n    | lat_deg =38.829645\n    | lon_deg =-77.306908\n    }}\n  {{Location map~ | GMU Fairfax\n    | label =Center for the Arts\n    | label_size=50\n    | position =left\n    | lat_deg =38.8295035\n    | lon_deg =-77.3090658\n    }}\n  {{Location map~ | GMU Fairfax\n    | label =EagleBank Arena\n    | label_size=50\n    | position =left\n    | lat_deg =38.8272525\n    | lon_deg =-77.3081015\n    }}\n  {{Location map~ | GMU Fairfax\n    | label =Harris Theatre\n    | label_size=50\n    | position =top\n    | lat_deg =38.8302312\n    | lon_deg =-77.3091418\n    }}\n  {{Location map~ | GMU Fairfax\n    | label =Southside Dining\n    | label_size=50\n    | position =right\n    | lat_deg =38.8312185\n    | lon_deg =-77.3062596\n    }}\n  {{Location map~ | GMU Fairfax\n    | label =Innovation\n    | label_size=50\n    | position =left\n    | lat_deg =38.8285105\n    | lon_deg =-77.3069287\n    }}\n  {{Location map~ | GMU Fairfax\n    | label =Enterprise\n    | label_size=50\n    | position =bottom\n    | lat_deg =38.8285105\n    | lon_deg =-77.3069287\n    }}\n  {{Location map~ | GMU Fairfax\n    | label =Research\n    | label_size=50\n    | position =right\n    | lat_deg =38.8285105\n    | lon_deg =-77.3069287\n    }}\n{{Location map~ | GMU Fairfax\n    | label =George Mason Statue\n    | label_size=50\n    | position =top\n    | lat_deg =38.8302699\n    | lon_deg =-77.3085923\n    }}\n}}\n| image_skyline                   = File:An aerial view of the Johnson Center at dawn..jpg\n| image_caption                   = Johnson Center and Center for the Arts\n| subdivision_name5               = [[George Mason, Virginia|George Mason]]\n| subdivision_type5               = [[Census-Designated Place]]\n| subdivision_type4               = [[Post Town|Post Town Name]]\n| official_name                   = \n| subdivision_name3               = ([[unincorporated area]])\n| subdivision_type3               = [[City]] or [[Town]]\n| subdivision_name2               = {{Flagicon image|Flag of Fairfax County, Virginia.svg}} [[Fairfax County, Virginia|Fairfax County]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[County]]\n| subdivision_name1               = {{flagicon image|Flag of Virginia.svg}} [[Virginia]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{flagcountry|United States}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name6               = \n| postal_code_type                = [[Zip Code]]\n| postal_code                     = 22030\n| settlement_type                 = [[Campus|University Campus]]\n}}\nThe university's Fairfax Campus is situated on {{Convert|677|acres|sqmi}} of landscaped land with a large pond in a suburban environment in [[George Mason, Virginia]], just south of the [[Fairfax, Virginia|City of Fairfax]] in central [[Fairfax County]]. Off-campus amenities are within walking distance and [[Washington, D.C.]] is approximately {{Convert|20|miles|km}} from campus.{{efn |<ref>{{cite web |url=http://shuttle.gmu.edu/ |title=Mason Shuttles |website=gmu.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fairfaxva.gov/CUEBus/CUEBus.asp |accessdate=February 5, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130617025457/http://www.fairfaxva.gov/CUEBus/CUEBus.asp |archivedate=June 17, 2013 |title=CUE Bus System}}</ref>}} Notable buildings include the {{Convert|320000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} student union building, the Johnson Center; the Center for the Arts, a 2,000-seat concert hall; the {{Convert|180000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} Long and Kimmy Nguyen Engineering Building; Exploratory Hall for science, new in 2013; an astronomy observatory and telescope; the {{Convert|88900|sqft|m2|adj=on}} Art and Design Building; the newly expanded Fenwick Library, and will soon reconstruct the academic buildings Robinson A and B;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://facilities.gmu.edu/projects/view-project.cfm?customel_dataPageID_2336=2453 |title=View a Project :: Facilities :: George Mason University |website=gmu.edu|access-date=February 5, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305005504/http://facilities.gmu.edu/projects/view-project.cfm?customel_dataPageID_2336=2453|archive-date=March 5, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> the [[Krasnow Institute for Advanced Study|Krasnow Institute]]; and three fully appointed gyms and an aquatic center for student use.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://recreation.gmu.edu/ |title=Recreation \u2013 George Mason University |website=gmu.edu}}</ref> The stadiums for indoor and outdoor track and field, baseball, softball, tennis, soccer and lacrosse are also on the Fairfax campus,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gomason.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=205054675&DB_OEM_ID=25200&DB_OEM_ID=25200%7ctitle=Facilities%7cwork=gomason.com |title=Facilities |website=gomason.com |accessdate=August 5, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924022956/http://www.gomason.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=205054675&DB_OEM_ID=25200&DB_OEM_ID=25200%7Ctitle%3DFacilities%7Cwork%3Dgomason.com |archivedate=September 24, 2015}}</ref> as is Masonvale, a housing community for faculty, staff and graduate students.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.masonvale.com/fairfax-va-apartments.asp |title=Masonvale Apartments &#124; Faculty & Staff Housing in Fairfax VA |website=Masonvale.com |date= |accessdate=February 1, 2016}}</ref> The smallest building on the campus is the {{Convert|33|sqft|m2|adj=on}} information booth.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://about.gmu.edu/mason-buildings/ |title=Mason Buildings |work=About Mason |access-date = February 5, 2016 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150710054506/http://about.gmu.edu/mason-buildings/ |archive-date = July 10, 2015 |url-status = dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==== Transportation ====\n[[File:City-University-Energysaver.jpg|220px|left|thumbnail|Fairfax City CUE Bus at Vienna, Fairfax, GMU station{{efn|All four Fairfax city bus routes travel between the Metrorail Vienna, Fairfax, GMU station and the Fairfax campus.}}]]\n\nThis campus is served by the [[Washington Metro]] [[Orange Line (Washington Metro)|Orange Line]] at the [[Vienna station (Washington Metro)|Vienna, Fairfax, GMU]] station as well as [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] routes.<ref name=\"metrovienna\">{{cite web |author=Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority |title=Vienna/Fairfax-GMU |url=http://www.wmata.com/rail/station_detail.cfm?station_id=103 |accessdate=September 30, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001175134/http://www.wmata.com/rail/station_detail.cfm?station_id=103 |archivedate=October 1, 2015}}</ref> The [[CUE Bus]] Green One, Green Two, Gold One, and Gold Two lines all provide service to this campus at {{Coord| 38.8347|-77.3070 |name=Cue Bus Stop}}.<ref name=\"cue\">{{cite web |author=City of Fairfax |title=CUE Bus Map and Schedule |url=http://www.fairfaxva.gov/government/public-works/transportation-division/cue-bus/cue-bus-map-and-schedule |accessdate=September 30, 2015 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151001081753/http://www.fairfaxva.gov/government/public-works/transportation-division/cue-bus/cue-bus-map-and-schedule |archive-date = October 1, 2015 |url-status = dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> This campus is served by the [[Virginia Railway Express]] [[Manassas Line]] at the [[Burke Centre (VRE station)|Burke Center station]].<ref name=\"vre\">{{cite web |author=Virginia Railway Express |title=General Schedule Information |url=http://www.vre.org/service/schedule.htm |accessdate=September 30, 2015}}</ref> [[Fairfax Connector]] Route 306: GMU\u2013Pentagon provides service to this campus.<ref name=\"FairfaxConnector\">{{cite web |author=County of Fairfax |title=Fairfax Area Routes |url=http://www.fairfaxcounty.gov/connector/routes/fairfax.htm |accessdate=September 30, 2015 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151001123703/http://www.fairfaxcounty.gov/connector/routes/fairfax.htm |archive-date = October 1, 2015 |url-status = dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Mason provides shuttle service between this campus and Vienna, Fairfax, GMU Metro station, the Burke Center VRE station, the Science and Technology Campus, West Campus, and downtown City of Fairfax.<ref name=\"MasonShuttles\">{{cite web |author=George Mason University |title=Mason Shuttles |url=http://shuttle.gmu.edu/ |accessdate=September 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<br />\n===Arlington===\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Arlington Campus\n| official_name                   = \n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flagcountry|United States}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = {{flagicon image|Flag of Virginia.svg}} [[Virginia]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[County]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[File:Flag of Arlington County, Virginia.svg|23px]]  [[Arlington County, Virginia|Arlington County]]\n| subdivision_type3               = [[City]] or [[Town]]\n| subdivision_name3               = ([[unincorporated area]])\n| subdivision_type4               = [[Post Town|Post Town Name]]\n| subdivision_name4               = Arlington\n| subdivision_type5               = [[Census-Designated Place]]\n| subdivision_name5               = \n| image_caption                   = Original Building, Van Metre Hall, Vernon Smith Hall, and Hazel Hall\n| image_skyline                   = File:George.Mason.University.Arlington.Campus.jpg\n| image_map                       = {{Location map+ | GMU Arlington\n| width = 300\n| places =\n  {{Location map~ | GMU Arlington\n    | label = Original Building\n    | position = left\n    | lat_deg = 38.8848469\n    | lon_deg = -77.1016176\n    }}\n  {{Location map~ | GMU Arlington\n    | label = Founders Hall\n    | position = bottom\n    | lat_deg = 38.885243\n    | lon_deg = -77.101288\n    }}\n  {{Location map~ | GMU Arlington\n    | label = Hazel Hall\n    | position = right\n    | lat_deg = 38.885348\n    | lon_deg = -77.100435\n    }}\n  {{Location map~ | GMU Arlington\n    | label = Vernon Smith Hall\n    | position = top\n    | lat_deg = 38.885527\n    | lon_deg = -77.101851\n    }}\n  {{Location map~ | GMU Arlington\n    | label = Metro Rail\n    | position = left\n    | lat_deg = 38.883682\n    | lon_deg = -77.102468\n    }}\n}}\n| parts_type                      = \n| parts                           = \n| subdivision_type6               = [[List of neighborhoods in Arlington County, Virginia|Neighborhood of Arlington]]\n| subdivision_name6               = [[Virginia Square, Arlington, Virginia|Virginia Square]]\n| postal_code_type                = [[Zip Code]]\n| postal_code                     = 22201\n| settlement_type                 = [[Campus|University Campus]]\n}}\n\nThe Arlington Campus is situated on {{convert|5.2|acres|m2 sqmi}} in [[Virginia Square, Arlington, Virginia|Virginia Square]], a bustling urban environment on the edge of [[Arlington, Virginia]]'s [[Clarendon, Arlington, Virginia|Clarendon]] business district and {{convert|4|miles|km|spell=in}} from downtown Washington, D.C. The campus was founded in 1979 with the acquisition of a law school;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ahistoryofmason.gmu.edu/exhibits/show/prominence/contents/schooloflaw |title=A History of George Mason University \u2013 1978\u20131996: Emergence : The Law School Battle\u2026and Triumph |website=gmu.edu}}</ref> in 1998 Hazel Hall opened to house the [[George Mason University School of Law|Mason School of Law]]; subsequent development created Van Metre Hall (formerly Founders Hall), home of the [[Schar School of Policy and Government]],<ref name=\"spgia.gmu.edu\">{{cite web |url=http://spgia.gmu.edu/ |title=School of Policy, Government, and International Affairs |accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref> the Center for Regional Analysis,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cra.gmu.edu/ |title=Center for Regional Analysis |website=gmu.edu |accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref> and the graduate-level administrative offices for the School of Business.<ref name=\"gmu.edu\" /> Vernon Smith Hall houses the School for Conflict Analysis and Resolution, the [[Mercatus Center]], and the [[Institute for Humane Studies]]. The campus also houses the 300-seat Founders Hall Auditorium.\n\nThe Arlington Campus is also the future home of the Mason School of Computing, a plan intended to double the number of computer science students to 15,000 over the next five years. As part of [[Amazon HQ2|Amazon's HQ2]] development in nearby [[Crystal City, Arlington, Virginia|Crystal City]], Mason announced [https://www2.gmu.edu/news/572891 a slew of new changes] to be made to the Arlington Campus. It committed to expanding the campus and [https://www2.gmu.edu/news/583031 replacing Original Building] with a 400,000sq ft mixed use high rise which would developed [https://www.virginiabusiness.com/article/george-mason-university-seeking-developer-for-arlington-campus-expansion/ in a public private partnership] to allow for mixed use commercial space on lower levels. The university also announced the development of an [https://content.gmu.edu/news/582631 Institute for Digital InnovAtion (IDIA)] to include labs, coworking and public programming spaces, ground-floor retail, a parking garage and a public plaza\n\nThe university has said they will invest $250 million at the Arlington Campus in the next five years, adding 1,000 faculty members and enlarging the campus to 1.2 million square feet, with an emphasis on computing programs and advanced research in high-tech fields. \n\n==== Transportation ====\n[[File:Virginia Sq-GMU station entrance pylon at night.jpg|thumbnail|left|Arlington campus subway stop]]\n\nThis campus is served by the Washington Metro Orange Line at the [[Virginia Square-GMU]] station, a campus shuttle service, and [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] route 38B.{{efn |<ref name=\"metrovasq\">{{cite web |author=Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority |title=Virginia Square-GMU |url=http://www.wmata.com/rail/station_detail.cfm?station_id=98 |accessdate=October 16, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081212065920/http://www.wmata.com/rail/station_detail.cfm?station_id=98 |archivedate=December 12, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"mapparkarl\" />}} The rail station is located one block west of the campus.\n\n<ref name=\"mapparkarl\" /> [[Arlington Transit|Arlington Rapid Transit or ART Bus]] routes 41, 42, and 75 also provide service at this location.<ref name=\"metrovasq\" /> The campus offers one electric vehicle charging station, five disabled permit automotive parking locations, three bicycle parking locations, and one [[Capital Bikeshare|Capitol Bikeshare]] location.<ref name=\"mapparkarl\">{{cite web |last=Kisielewski |first=Dennis |title=Arlington Campus Information |url=http://info.gmu.edu/Maps/ArlingtonMap15.pdf |publisher=George Mason University |accessdate=October 16, 2015 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150922012137/http://info.gmu.edu/Maps/ArlingtonMap15.pdf |archive-date = September 22, 2015 |url-status = dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n=== Science and Technology ===\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = SciTech Campus\n| subdivision_type3               = [[City]] or [[Town]]\n| postal_code                     = 20110\n| postal_code_type                = [[Zip Code]]\n| other_name                      = Prince William Campus <br> Manassas Campus\n| subdivision_name6               = \n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flagcountry|United States}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = {{flagicon image|Flag of Virginia.svg}} [[Virginia]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[County]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[File:Flag of Prince William County, Virginia.png|23px]] [[Prince William County, Virginia|Prince William County]]\n| subdivision_name3               = ([[unincorporated area]])\n| subdivision_name4               =  [[Manassas, Virginia|Manassas]]\n| official_name                   = Science and Technology Campus\n| subdivision_type4               = [[Post Town|Post Town Name]]\n| subdivision_type5               = [[Census-Designated Place]]\n| subdivision_name5               = \n| image_caption                   = Beacon Hall, Hylton Performing Arts Center, the EDGE, Life Sciences Laboratory, Discovery Hall, Occoquan Building, Freedom Aquatic and Fitness Center, Bull Run Hall, Biomedical Research Laboratory{{efn|from left to right}}\n| image_skyline                   = File:Aerial Photo of the Prince William Campus..jpg\n| image_map                       = \n| parts_type                      = \n| parts                           = \n| subdivision_type6               = \n| settlement_type                 = [[Campus|University Campus]]\n}}\n\nThe Science and Technology campus opened on August 25, 1997 as the Prince William campus in [[Manassas, Virginia]], on {{convert|134|acres|sqmi m2}} of land, some still currently undeveloped.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ahistoryofmason.gmu.edu/exhibits/show/presence/contents/princewilliamcampus |title=A History of George Mason University \u2013 1996\u20132012: Prominence : The Prince Wiliam Campus |website=gmu.edu}}</ref> More than 4,000 students are enrolled in classes in [[bioinformatics]], [[biotechnology]], information technology, and forensic [[biosciences]] educational and research programs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://irr.gmu.edu/factbooks/1314/Factbook1314_Enrollment.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=April 7, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630175601/http://irr.gmu.edu/factbooks/1314/Factbook1314_Enrollment.pdf |archive-date=June 30, 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref> There are undergraduate programs in health, fitness and recreation. There are graduate programs in exercise, fitness, health, geographic information systems, and facility management. Much of the research takes place in the high-security Biomedical Research Laboratory.<ref name=\"ncbid.cos.gmu.edu\">{{cite web |url=http://ncbid.cos.gmu.edu/ |title=National Center for Biodefense and Infectious Diseases |website=gmu.edu |accessdate=August 5, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905234122/http://ncbid.cos.gmu.edu/ |archive-date=September 5, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The 1,123-seat Merchant Hall and the 300-seat Verizon Auditorium in the Hylton Performing Arts Center opened in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hyltoncenter.org/ |title=Hylton Performing Arts Center |website=hyltoncenter.org |accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>Trescott, Jacqueline (April 29, 2010). \"George Mason University gets ready to raise a new curtain\". Washington Post. p. C2.</ref>\n\nThe 110,000-square-foot Freedom Aquatic and Fitness Center is operated by the Mason Enterprise Center.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freedom-center.com/ |title=Fitness, Pool and Gym \u2013 Freedom Aquatic and Fitness Center \u2013 Manassas, Virginia |website=freedom-center.com |accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref> The Mason Center for Team and Organizational Learning stylized as EDGE is an experiential education facility open to the public.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edgeatmason.com/ |title=The EDGE \u2013 Team Building Ropes Course and Outdoors Activities \u2013 Virginia, DC, Maryland |website=edgeatmason.com |accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref> The Sports Medicine Assessment Research and Testing lab stylized as SMART Lab is located within the Freedom center. The SMART Lab is most known for its [[concussion]] research.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://smartlab.gmu.edu/about/ |title=About Us |website=smartlab.gmu.edu |access-date = September 24, 2016}}</ref> On April 23, 2015 the campus was renamed to the Science and Technology Campus.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gov. McAuliffe Joins George Mason University to Launch Institute for Advanced Biomedical Research |url=http://newsdesk.gmu.edu/2015/04/governor-mcauliffe-joins-george-mason-university-to-launch-institute-for-advanced-biomedical-research/ |accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n\n\nIn 2019, the university engaged in a feasibility study of creating a medical school at the Prince William Campus. The proposed medical school would be completed in 2022.<ref>Clabaugh, J. (2019, June 20). George Mason University to consider adding a medical school. WTOP. Retrieved from https://wtop.com/business-finance/2019/06/george-mason-university-to-consider-adding-a-medical-school/</ref><ref>Sides, E. (2019, November 16). George Mason University to layout timeline for proposed medical school at Prince William campus. Inside Nova. Retrieved from https://www.insidenova.com/news/education/prince_william/george-mason-university-to-layout-timeline-for-proposed-medical-school/article_0b28b2ae-07d2-11ea-bf21-0fc35919f090.html</ref>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n=== Smithsonian-Mason School of Conservation ===\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Front Royal Campus\n| subdivision_name4               = \n| subdivision_type6               = \n| parts                           = \n| parts_type                      = \n| image_map                       = \n| image_skyline                   = File:Smithsonian-Mason School of Conservation.jpg\n| image_caption                   = Academic Center, G.T. Halpin Family Living & Learning Community,{{efn|Residential Facility}} Dining Commons{{efn|from left to right}}<nowiki>]]</nowiki>\n| subdivision_name5               = \n| subdivision_type5               = [[Census-Designated Place]]\n| subdivision_type4               = [[Post Town|Post Town Name]]\n| official_name                   = [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian]]-Mason School of Conservation\n| subdivision_name3               =  [[Front Royal, Virginia|Front Royal]]\n| subdivision_type3               = [[City]] or [[Town]]\n| subdivision_name2               =  [[Warren County, Virginia|Warren County]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[County]]\n| subdivision_name1               = {{flagicon image|Flag of Virginia.svg}} [[Virginia]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{flagcountry|United States}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name6               = \n| other_name                      = Smithsonian-Mason <br> Blue Ridge campus\n| postal_code_type                = [[Zip Code]]\n| postal_code                     = 22630\n| settlement_type                 = [[Campus|University Campus]]\n}}\n\n\nThe campus in [[Front Royal, Virginia]] is a collaboration between the [[Smithsonian Institution]] and the university.<ref name=\"factsheet\">{{cite magazine |author=National Zoological Park |title=Smithsonian-Mason School of Conservation Facilities and Program Fact Sheet |url=http://nationalzoo.si.edu/Publications/PressMaterials/PressKit/SIMason/SImasonfacility.cfm |magazine=Smithsonian |accessdate=October 17, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907191801/http://nationalzoo.si.edu/Publications/PressMaterials/PressKit/SIMason/SIMasonfacility.cfm |archivedate=September 7, 2015}}</ref> Open to students in August 2012 after breaking ground on the project on June 29, 2011, the primary focus of the campus is global conservation training.<ref name=\"factsheet\" /> The Volgenau Academic Center includes three teaching laboratories, four classrooms, and 18 offices.<ref name=\"factsheet\" /> [[Shenandoah National Park]] is visible from the dining facility's indoor and outdoor seating.<ref name=\"factsheet\" /> Living quarters include 60 double occupancy rooms, an exercise facility, and study space.<ref name=\"factsheet\" />\n\n=== Mason Korea (Songdo, South Korea) ===\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Mason Korea\n| subdivision_type3               = International Business District\n| postal_code                     = 21985\n| postal_code_type                = Postal Code\n| subdivision_name6               = \n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flagcountry|South Korea}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Regions of Korea|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Seoul Capital Area|Seoul Capital Area (Sudogwon)]]\n| subdivision_type2               = Metropolitan City\n| subdivision_name2               = [[File:Flag of Incheon.svg|23px]] [[Incheon]]\n| subdivision_name3               = [[Songdo International Business District|Songdo]]\n| subdivision_name4               = \n| official_name                   = Songdo Campus <br> {{Korean|hangul=\uc1a1\ub3c4 \ucea0\ud37c\uc2a4}}\n| subdivision_type4               = [[Post Town|Post Town Name]]\n| subdivision_type5               = [[Census-Designated Place]]\n| subdivision_name5               = \n| image_caption                   = Data Center, Library, Guest House, Student's Hall{{efn|from left to right}}\n| image_skyline                   = File:Songdo Campus, Mason Korea..jpg\n| image_map                       = \n| parts_type                      = \n| parts                           = \n| subdivision_type6               = \n| settlement_type                 = [[Campus|University Campus]]\n| other_name                      = Korea Campus\n}}\nOpened in March 2014, the Songdo campus is in South Korea's Incheon Free Economic Zone, a {{convert|42000|acres|sqmi|adj=on}} site designed for 850,000 people. It's {{convert|25|mi|km}} from Seoul and a two-hour flight from China and Japan, and is connected to the [[Seoul Metropolitan Subway]].\n\nThe Commonwealth of Virginia considers the Songdo campus legally no different than any other Mason campus, \"... board of visitors shall have the same powers with respect to operation and governance of its branch campus in Korea as are vested in the board by the [[Code of Virginia]] with respect to George Mason University in Virginia ...\"<ref name=\"Petersen2010\">{{Citation |last=Petersen |first=J. Chapman |title=Establishment of branch campus in the Republic of Korea |accessdate=May 8, 2016 |date=April 12, 2010 |url=http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/title23/chapter9.1/section23-91.29:1/}}</ref>\n\nMason Korea students will spend the sixth and seventh semesters (one year) on the Fairfax Campus, with all other course work to be completed in Songdo. George Mason University Korea offers seven undergraduate programs: Management, Finance, Accounting, Economics, Global Affairs, Conflict Analysis and Resolution, and Computer Game Design. Mason Korea also has two graduate programs: Systems Engineering and IB & ESOL.\n\nMason Korea's first commencement class graduated in December 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://koreabizwire.com/incheon-global-campus-slowly-coming-to-fruition/104489?ckattempt=3 |website=koreabizwire.com|access-date=June 14, 2019 |title=Incheon Global Campus Slowly Coming to Fruition}}</ref> Students from Mason Korea earn the same diploma as home campus students, with English as the language of instruction.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n== Academics and rankings ==\nMason offers undergraduate, master's, law, and doctoral degrees.<ref name=\"Factbook\" /> The student-faculty ratio is 17:1; 58 percent of undergraduate classes have fewer than 30 students and 30 percent of undergraduate classes have fewer than 20 students.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://irr2.gmu.edu/cds/cds_new/sec_action.cfm?year=2018-19&sec_id=I |title=Office of Institutional Effectiveness and Planning |website=irr2.gmu.edu|access-date=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Colleges and schools===\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n<!-- U.S. rankings -->\n| Forbes = 177\n| THE_WSJ = 184\n| USNWR_NU = 153\n| Wamo_NU = 51\n<!-- Global rankings -->\n| USNWR_W = 434\n| THES_W = 251\u2013300\n| QS_W = 801\u20131000\n| ARWU_W = 201\u2013300\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border:0; text-align:center; line-height:100%;\"\n! colspan=13 style=\"text-align: center; font-weight: bold;\" | Colleges and Schools of George Mason University\n|- style=\"font-weight: bold;\"\n|| Historical name\n|| Current name\n|-\n| rowspan=2 style=\"text-align: center;\" | College of Arts and Sciences 1957\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | College of Humanities and Social Sciences 2006<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chss.gmu.edu/ |title=College of Humanities and Social Sciences |work=gmu.edu |accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | College of Science 2006<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cos.gmu.edu/ |title=College of Science |work=gmu.edu |accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|| School of Business Administration 1977\n|| School of Business 2014<ref name=\"gmu.edu\">{{cite web |url=http://business.gmu.edu/ |title=George Mason University - School of Business |website=business.gmu.edu}}</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|| School of Law 1979\n|| [[Antonin Scalia Law School]] 2016{{refn| Name change to Antonin Scalia School of Law:\n* {{cite web |last=Chappell |first=Bill |title=Plan For Antonin Scalia School Of Law Is Tweaked Over Unfortunate Acronym |work=The Two-Way Breaking News from NPR |accessdate=April 6, 2016 |date=April 6, 2016 |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2016/04/06/473228688/plan-for-antonin-scalia-school-of-law-is-tweaked-over-unfortunate-acronym}}\n* {{Cite news |last=Neil |first=Martha |title=George Mason law school to take name of late Supreme Court Justice Antonin Scalia |work=ABA Journal |accessdate=April 1, 2016 |date=March 31, 2016 |url=http://www.abajournal.com/news/article/george_mason_to_take_name_of_late_supreme_